  "prompt": "If Buddhism is not a religion, then what is it?",
  "response": "Buddhism is often described as a complex philosophical and spiritual tradition that doesn't fit neatly into the conventional Western understanding of \"religion.\" Different perspectives characterize Buddhism as:\n\n1. A Philosophy\n- A system of ethical and philosophical teachings\n- Focused on understanding human suffering and personal transformation\n- Emphasizes rational inquiry and personal experience\n\n2. A Psychological Practice\n- Provides methods for understanding the mind\n- Offers techniques for mental training and self-awareness\n- Includes meditation as a core practice for exploring consciousness\n\n3. A Way of Life\n- A set of practices and principles for living\n- Emphasizes compassion, mindfulness, and personal development\n- Guides individuals toward understanding reality and reducing suffering\n\n4. A Contemplative Tradition\n- Encourages deep self-reflection\n- Promotes understanding of human nature\n- Seeks insight into the nature of existence\n\n5. A Spiritual Path\n- Focuses on personal growth and enlightenment\n- Offers methods for transcending suffering\n- Provides a framework for understanding human experience\n\nSome scholars and practitioners argue that Buddhism is \"non-theistic\" because it doesn't center on worshipping a supreme deity, which distinguishes it from many traditional religions. However, some Buddhist traditions do incorporate devotional and ritualistic elements.\n\nUltimately, Buddhism can be seen as a multifaceted approach to understanding human experience and personal transformation.",
